#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:7
msgid "Creating a Bloom Filter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md
msgid ""
"Demonstrates how to create a bloom filter using Python and represent it "
"in a filterload message."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:9
msgid ""
"In this section, we'll use variable names that correspond to the field "
"names in the [`filterload` message documentation](../reference/p2p-"
"network-control-messages.md#filterload). Each code block precedes the "
"paragraph describing it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:20
msgid ""
"We start by setting some maximum values defined in "
"[BIP37](https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/blob/master/bip-0037.mediawiki): "
"the maximum number of bytes allowed in a filter and the maximum number of"
" hash functions used to hash each piece of data.  We also set nFlags to "
"zero, indicating we don't want the remote node to update the filter for "
"us. (We won't use nFlags again in the sample program, but real programs "
"will need to use it.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:27
msgid ""
"We define the number (n) of elements we plan to insert into the filter "
"and the false positive rate (p) we want to help protect our privacy. For "
"this example, we will set *n* to one element and *p* to a rate of "
"1-in-10,000 to produce a small and precise filter for illustration "
"purposes. In actual use, your filters will probably be much larger."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:38
msgid ""
"Using the formula described in "
"[BIP37](https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/blob/master/bip-0037.mediawiki), "
"we calculate the ideal size of the filter (in bytes) and the ideal number"
" of hash functions to use. Both are truncated down to the nearest whole "
"number and both are also constrained to the maximum values we defined "
"earlier. The results of this particular fixed computation are 2 filter "
"bytes and 11 hash functions. We then use *nFilterBytes* to create a "
"little-endian bit array of the appropriate size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:44
msgid ""
"We also should choose a value for *nTweak*.  In this case, we'll simply "
"use zero."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:55
msgid ""
"We setup our hash function template using the formula and 0xfba4c795 "
"constant set in "
"[BIP37](https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/blob/master/bip-0037.mediawiki). "
"Note that we limit the size of the seed to four bytes and that we're "
"returning the result of the hash modulo the size of the filter in bits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:63
msgid ""
"For the data to add to the filter, we're adding a "
"[TXID](../resources/glossary.md#transaction-identifiers). Note that the "
"TXID is in [internal byte order](../resources/glossary.md#internal-byte-"
"order)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:87
msgid ""
"Now we use the hash function template to run a slightly different hash "
"function for *nHashFuncs* times. The result of each function being run on"
" the transaction is used as an index number: the bit at that index is set"
" to 1. We can see this in the printed debugging output:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:108
msgid ""
"Notice that in iterations 8 and 9, the filter did not change because the "
"corresponding bit was already set in a previous iteration (5 and 7, "
"respectively).  This is a normal part of [bloom "
"filter](../resources/glossary.md#bloom-filter) operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:110
msgid ""
"We only added one element to the filter above, but we could repeat the "
"process with additional elements and continue to add them to the same "
"filter. (To maintain the same false-positive rate, you would need a "
"larger filter size as computed earlier.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:112
msgid ""
"Note: for a more optimized Python implementation with fewer external "
"dependencies, see [python-bitcoinlib's](https://github.com/petertodd"
"/python-bitcoinlib) bloom filter module which is based directly on "
"Bitcoin Core's C++ implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-creating-a-bloom-filter.md:114
msgid ""
"Using the [`filterload` message](../reference/p2p-network-control-"
"messages.md#filterload) format, the complete filter created above would "
"be the binary form of the annotated hexdump shown below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-evaluating-a-bloom-filter.md
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-evaluating-a-bloom-filter.md:7
msgid "Evaluating a Bloom Filter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-evaluating-a-bloom-filter.md
msgid ""
"Demonstrates how to check if a bloom filter finds any data matching the "
"relevant criteria."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-evaluating-a-bloom-filter.md:9
msgid ""
"Using a [bloom filter](../resources/glossary.md#bloom-filter) to find "
"matching data is nearly identical to constructing a bloom filter---except"
" that at each step we check to see if the calculated index bit is set in "
"the existing filter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-evaluating-a-bloom-filter.md:19
msgid ""
"Using the bloom filter created above, we import its various parameters. "
"Note, as indicated in the section above, we won't actually use *nFlags* "
"to update the filter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-evaluating-a-bloom-filter.md:35
msgid ""
"We define a function to check an element against the provided filter. "
"When checking whether the filter might contain an element, we test to see"
" whether a particular bit in the filter is already set to 1 (if it isn't,"
" the match fails)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-evaluating-a-bloom-filter.md:45
msgid ""
"Testing the filter against the data element we previously added, we get "
"no output (indicating a possible match).  Recall that bloom filters have "
"a zero false negative rate---so they should always match the inserted "
"elements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-evaluating-a-bloom-filter.md:53
msgid ""
"Testing the filter against an arbitrary element, we get the failure "
"output below.  Note: we created the filter with a 1-in-10,000 false "
"positive rate (which was rounded up somewhat when we truncated), so it "
"was possible this arbitrary string would've matched the filter anyway. It"
" is not possible to set a bloom filter to a false positive rate of zero, "
"so your program will always have to deal with false positives. The output"
" below shows us that one of the hash functions returned an index number "
"of 0x06, but that bit wasn't set in the filter, causing the match "
"failure:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:7
msgid "Parsing a MerkleBlock"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md
msgid ""
"In this section we will parse a merkle block after having retrieved it "
"from the network."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:9
msgid ""
"In the section above, we retrieved a [merkle "
"block](../resources/glossary.md#merkle-block) from the network; now we "
"will parse it. Most of the [block header](../resources/glossary.md#block-"
"header) has been omitted. For a more complete hexdump, see the example in"
" the [`merkleblock` message section](../reference/p2p-network-data-"
"messages.md#merkleblock)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:31
msgid ""
"We parse the above [`merkleblock` message](../reference/p2p-network-data-"
"messages.md#merkleblock) using the following instructions.  Each "
"illustration is described in the paragraph below it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:33
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-001.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:33
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:37
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:41
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:45
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:49
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:53
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:57
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:61
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:65
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:69
msgid "Parsing A MerkleBlock"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:35
msgid ""
"We start by building the structure of a [merkle "
"tree](../resources/glossary.md#merkle-tree) based on the number of "
"[transactions](../resources/glossary.md#transaction) in the "
"[block](../resources/glossary.md#block)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:37
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-002.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:39
msgid ""
"The first flag is a 1 and the [merkle root](../resources/glossary.md"
"#merkle-root) is (as always) a non-TXID node, so we will need to compute "
"the hash later based on this node's children. Accordingly, we descend "
"into the merkle root's left child and look at the next flag for "
"instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:41
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-003.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:43
msgid ""
"The next flag in the example is a 0 and this is also a non-TXID node, so "
"we apply the first hash from the [`merkleblock` message](../reference"
"/p2p-network-data-messages.md#merkleblock) to this node. We also don't "
"process any child nodes---according to the peer which created the "
"[`merkleblock` message](../reference/p2p-network-data-"
"messages.md#merkleblock), none of those nodes will lead to "
"[TXIDs](../resources/glossary.md#transaction-identifiers) of transactions"
" that match our filter, so we don't need them. We go back up to the "
"merkle root and then descend into its right child and look at the next "
"(third) flag for instructions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:45
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-004.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:47
msgid ""
"The third flag in the example is another 1 on another non-TXID node, so "
"we descend into its left child."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:49
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-005.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:51
msgid ""
"The fourth flag is also a 1 on another non-TXID node, so we descend again"
"---we will always continue descending until we reach a TXID node or a "
"non-TXID node with a 0 flag (or we finish filling out the tree)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:53
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-006.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:55
msgid ""
"Finally, on the fifth flag in the example (a 1), we reach a TXID node. "
"The 1 flag indicates this TXID's transaction matches our filter and that "
"we should take the next (second) hash and use it as this node's TXID."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:57
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-007.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:59
msgid ""
"The sixth flag also applies to a TXID, but it's a 0 flag, so this TXID's "
"transaction doesn't match our filter; still, we take the next (third) "
"hash and use it as this node's TXID."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:61
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-008.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:63
msgid ""
"We now have enough information to compute the hash for the fourth node we"
" encountered---it's the hash of the concatenated hashes of the two TXIDs "
"we filled out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:65
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-009.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:67
msgid ""
"Moving to the right child of the third node we encountered, we fill it "
"out using the seventh flag and final hash---and discover there are no "
"more child nodes to process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:69
msgid ""
"![Parsing A MerkleBlock](../../img/dev/gifs/en-merkleblock-parsing/en-"
"merkleblock-parsing-011.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:71
msgid ""
"We hash as appropriate to fill out the tree.  Note that the eighth flag "
"is not used---this is acceptable as it was required to pad out a flag "
"byte."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-parsing-a-merkleblock.md:73
msgid ""
"The final steps would be to ensure the computed [merkle "
"root](../resources/glossary.md#merkle-root) is identical to the merkle "
"root in the [header](../resources/glossary.md#header) and check the other"
" steps of the parsing checklist in the [`merkleblock` "
"message](../reference/p2p-network-data-messages.md#merkleblock) section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-retrieving-a-merkleblock.md
#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-retrieving-a-merkleblock.md:7
msgid "Retrieving a MerkleBlock"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-retrieving-a-merkleblock.md
msgid ""
"This section walks through each step of the process, demonstrating basic "
"network communication and merkle block processing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-retrieving-a-merkleblock.md:9
msgid ""
"For the [`merkleblock` message](../reference/p2p-network-data-"
"messages.md#merkleblock) documentation on the reference page, an actual "
"[merkle block](../resources/glossary.md#merkle-block) was retrieved from "
"the [network](../resources/glossary.md#network) and manually processed.  "
"This section walks through each step of the process, demonstrating basic "
"network communication and merkle block processing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-retrieving-a-merkleblock.md:42
msgid ""
"To connect to the P2P [network](../resources/glossary.md#network), the "
"trivial Python function above was developed to compute message headers "
"and send payloads decoded from hex."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-retrieving-a-merkleblock.md:63
msgid ""
"Peers on the network will not accept any requests until you send them a "
"[`version` message](../reference/p2p-network-control-"
"messages.md#version). The receiving node will reply with their [`version`"
" message](../reference/p2p-network-control-messages.md#version) and a "
"[`verack` message](../reference/p2p-network-control-messages.md#verack)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/core/examples/p2p-network-retrieving-a-merkleblock.md:70
